00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,960
Alyasha said, Alyasha has this terrific religious experience, spiritual experience in the middle of the book.

2
00:00:09,280 --> 00:00:25,041
After he sees that Father Zosima has indeed performed a miracle by creating his love, which he then turns on Grushenka, and that creates a miracle for her, giving her a new option for acting, which is creative instead of destructive.

3
00:00:25,041 --> 00:00:26,080
Thanks a lot.

4
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:37,481
And then, Alyasha has the last comment by Dostoevsky is the transition I want to make.

5
00:00:37,481 --> 00:00:42,360
We were on 419 last time, and the experience is over.

6
00:00:43,001 --> 00:00:49,560
The last thing he says about it is, it sees the sovereignty of his mind for his life and forever.

7
00:00:49,561 --> 00:00:52,281
I don't know if I said it last time, but I'll say it again.

8
00:00:52,280 --> 00:01:00,681
For the Russian people listening who send me helpful comments every once in a while, it's too bad he says some idea sees the sovereignty of his mind.

9
00:01:00,681 --> 00:01:06,681
It would be nice if the Russian word was something like a conviction or a notion or something.

10
00:01:06,681 --> 00:01:08,681
An idea is too abstract.

11
00:01:08,920 --> 00:01:23,480
What sees him is a whole sense of what it is to be a human being in touch with all the other, all the other human beings, all the other worlds of God, that is, all the other people who love each other everywhere.

12
00:01:23,481 --> 00:01:25,960
And the final thing is something later.

13
00:01:26,201 --> 00:01:27,481
I finished this last time.

14
00:01:27,481 --> 00:01:29,160
I just summed it up.

15
00:01:29,160 --> 00:01:41,321
The one step on 419 that was after last time and begins this time is someone visited my soul in that hour, he used to say afterwards, with implicit faith.

16
00:01:41,321 --> 00:01:52,121
Now that's interesting and strange, because the normal way to hear that would be the someone would be Jesus, I suppose.

17
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:57,400
God the Father doesn't go around visiting people's souls, but it isn't.

18
00:01:57,400 --> 00:01:59,160
It's someone else.

19
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:11,321
And it's the same someone that points the way into the monastery for the mysterious visitor on 358.

20
00:02:11,321 --> 00:02:12,840
I mentioned it already.

21
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:31,600
The last thing he says, these final, these funny last things that Dostoevsky puts in, on 358, it says, I left the town, I entered, by God's grace, I entered upon the safe and blessed path, following the unseen finger that guided me so clearly to it.

22
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:32,161
Period.

23
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:33,600
Because then he talks about Michiel.

24
00:02:33,600 --> 00:02:35,840
But Michiel is not the unseen finger.

25
00:02:35,840 --> 00:02:48,321
The unseen finger is, you know, I think we talked about it, this sort of suddenly love explodes into the mind of Zosima as he's about to enter this duel.

26
00:02:48,321 --> 00:02:57,761
Who gave him the capacity for that mystical kind of total connected love that he suddenly experiences?

27
00:02:58,400 --> 00:02:59,840
His brother Markle.

28
00:02:59,840 --> 00:03:08,801
And he gave it to him by actually touching him and looking into his eyes and telling him to go out and live it.

29
00:03:09,681 --> 00:03:14,561
Let's see if I can open to that right away, where he tells him that.

30
00:03:14,561 --> 00:03:17,441
Yes, the middle of 329.

31
00:03:17,761 --> 00:03:18,881
I went into his room.

32
00:03:18,881 --> 00:03:21,920
I read it already, this quote in connection with the sun.

33
00:03:21,920 --> 00:03:36,480
Of course, when one of these amazingly important religious experiences, when getting in touch with the connectedness of everything and getting therefore agape love charged up in you, so there's always the sun rays.

34
00:03:36,481 --> 00:03:44,960
He beckoned me, he put his hands on my shoulders and looked into my face lovingly, and then he said, run and play now, enjoy life for me too.

35
00:03:44,960 --> 00:03:59,881
That's the moment that he gives him, he passes on to him this sort of supernatural, but not against science, but not normal nature either, agape experience.

36
00:04:00,201 --> 00:04:22,040
And I think I said it, but I'll say it one more time: that this is the existentializing of a not very interesting Christian notion, but it's something Dostoevsky's interested in: the passing on of the power to save people from Jesus to Peter and then to all the bishops from there on.

37
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:25,080
All they have their laying on of hands.

38
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:31,241
And Dostoevsky is saying, but that's just magic that you could pass this thing on by just laying your hands.

39
00:04:31,241 --> 00:04:37,881
But it gets passed on by these emotional experiences that stay in the memory of the people.

40
00:04:37,881 --> 00:04:46,040
So Alyasha's memory of his mother holding him up to the icon, Dimitri's memory of the German doctor giving him the pound of nuts.

41
00:04:46,040 --> 00:05:06,201
And now we get another one, Markle's memory, which he says a lot he doesn't remember, but boy, does he remember this, this moment when he sort of connects with his brother and the vision that his brother has of the love.

42
00:05:06,201 --> 00:05:08,921
So now we have to just look at Markle.

43
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:26,360
It should be clear, I hope, that Markle is the existentialized, unmagical, unmythical, but also normal, because not anti-science.

44
00:05:26,761 --> 00:05:33,001
Since science and religion are having such a fight these days, I want to keep saying Dostoevsky's got an answer.

45
00:05:33,001 --> 00:05:41,321
Don't go around arguing about whether Christianity or any other religion, but this is Christianity, is compatible with science.

46
00:05:41,321 --> 00:05:45,520
That only comes in if you think of Christianity in this magical way.

47
00:05:45,520 --> 00:05:53,761
But if you think of it in what is its existential meaning, what does it mean for human beings and how does it change the way they live?

48
00:05:53,761 --> 00:05:58,800
That's not a question for physics and chemistry, nor for neuroscience.

49
00:05:58,800 --> 00:06:02,721
Somebody came up afterwards and said, but now we know how it happens in the brain.

50
00:06:02,721 --> 00:06:17,200
Keep your eyes open later in the book, when, believe it or not, Gostovsky, who thinks of everything, has Rakitin talking to Dmitry about neurons, which have just been discovered, and saying, Well, now we know neurons do it.

51
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:22,481
You don't have to feel guilt, and you don't have to feel repentance, and you don't get redeemed.

52
00:06:23,200 --> 00:06:26,641
We know all now that that's all caused by neurons.

53
00:06:26,641 --> 00:06:35,361
And Alyasha's response is: if you'll keep your eye open for it, is not to answer Dimitri, but simply to ignore him.

54
00:06:35,361 --> 00:06:38,400
Meaning, in effect, that's just irrelevant.

55
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:47,601
The causal basis of agape love is fine, and certainly something goes on in the brain when you experience it.

56
00:06:47,601 --> 00:06:54,161
But there is also an existential meaning to it, and science can't deal with that meaning.

57
00:06:54,960 --> 00:06:59,201
But science doesn't refute the meaning, nor do the neurons.

58
00:06:59,761 --> 00:07:07,121
So now, Markle is going to be the existentialized version of the incarnation.

59
00:07:07,121 --> 00:07:18,801
The incarnation, meaning, you know, incarnate has to do with body, the word, namely the logos of the universe, becomes flesh in Jesus.

60
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:20,241
And what is that now?

61
00:07:20,241 --> 00:07:22,241
But all that is so strange.

62
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:26,641
Dostoevsky's got the job of saying, well, what does it really look like?

63
00:07:26,641 --> 00:07:42,280
Well, what he's going to do is sort of restage the original Christian sort of events as they would happen right now in order to capture what existential experience was going on.

64
00:07:42,601 --> 00:07:48,601
So the incarnate, every, I think he thinks that there can be a plurality of incarnations.

65
00:07:48,601 --> 00:07:50,520
Markle is one of them.

66
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:59,001
Jesus was the first one, and therefore very important, because without somebody starting this, there wouldn't have been anybody else doing it.

67
00:07:59,481 --> 00:08:01,001
And what is the this?

68
00:08:01,001 --> 00:08:06,921
Well, the incarnation means the embodiment of God.

69
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:16,121
Now, if God is the connectedness of everything with everything, what would it be to embody that?

70
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:18,200
Well, look at Markle.

71
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:27,001
It would be to feel in touch with the birds and the bees and the people and his mother and the animals and feel overwhelmed with joy about it and so forth.

72
00:08:27,001 --> 00:08:37,641
And so he exhibits, in effect, that everybody's connected and how everybody's connected and what to do about the fact that everybody's connected.

73
00:08:37,641 --> 00:08:42,201
That makes his story a story.

74
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:44,921
It's the incarnation.

75
00:08:46,121 --> 00:08:51,721
And now I will jump to what I want to do next.

76
00:08:54,280 --> 00:08:58,201
So he reveals, I just said what I need to say about that.

77
00:08:59,560 --> 00:09:01,001
And how does he talk?

78
00:09:01,001 --> 00:09:06,441
Well, he tells you all these things on 326 and 327.

79
00:09:06,440 --> 00:09:09,081
By the way, it may or may not be important.

80
00:09:09,081 --> 00:09:16,481
I think maybe it's because Markle is so important that on 326 it looks like Markle combines all the three brothers.

81
00:09:16,481 --> 00:09:25,520
Zostima says of him on 326 that he did well at school, and we know that he reminds him of Alyasha.

82
00:09:25,520 --> 00:09:29,761
He looks like Alyasha at the bottom of 324.

83
00:09:29,761 --> 00:09:36,321
Alyasha seems to me so like him spiritually that many times I've taken him for that young man.

84
00:09:36,320 --> 00:09:39,121
So he's sort of reincarnated.

85
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:43,041
He's the incarnation and then he's reincarnated in Alyasha.

86
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:50,161
That is, Alyasha is going to also embody the love and the connectedness.

87
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:51,761
And he's like Yvonne.

88
00:09:51,761 --> 00:09:56,801
And this is more important to us, that he's corrupted by philosophy.

89
00:09:57,361 --> 00:10:04,321
So about 10 lines down on 326, he did well at school and so forth.

90
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:12,801
Six months before his death, when he was 17, he made friends with a political exile who had been banished from Moscow to our town for free thinking.

91
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:17,201
That's sort of anti-religious secular thinking.

92
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:18,880
And led a solitary existence.

93
00:10:18,881 --> 00:10:21,920
This man was a scholar who gained distinction in philosophy.

94
00:10:21,920 --> 00:10:23,761
That's always a bad sign.

95
00:10:23,761 --> 00:10:30,321
Yvonne is a philosopher, or does what presumably natural philosophy, sort of philosophy of science.

96
00:10:30,320 --> 00:10:35,121
This guy does social philosophy, what will become something like Marxism.

97
00:10:35,121 --> 00:10:38,961
And all that's the wrong way to go, Dostoevsky thinks.

98
00:10:39,280 --> 00:10:42,160
But it has a corrupting effect on Markle.

99
00:10:42,160 --> 00:10:43,441
And that's important.

100
00:10:43,520 --> 00:10:44,960
So the next paragraph.

101
00:10:44,960 --> 00:10:47,520
It was the beginning of Lent, and Markle would not fast.

102
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:49,120
He was rude and laughed at it.

103
00:10:49,121 --> 00:10:54,641
That's all silly, and there is no God, he said, horrifying my mother and the servants, too.

104
00:10:54,641 --> 00:10:58,241
Well, that doesn't seem a very Jesus-like thing for him to do, does it?

105
00:10:58,241 --> 00:11:04,201
I mean, that he's saying there is no God and laughing at the people who are religious.

106
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:09,081
Well, that's one way that Dostoevsky deviates from the tradition.

107
00:11:09,081 --> 00:11:17,481
I mean, he's enough of a thinker on his own that he's not going to just tell you everything that the Russian Orthodox Church tells you.

108
00:11:17,481 --> 00:11:45,721
And he's got this theory, which I told you once already, and since time is running out, I'm just going to remind you that unless these saving people have already had some experience which shows them what it is to be brutal and evil and selfish and so forth, they can't understand the other, the suffering of others and the tendency of others to sin.

109
00:11:45,721 --> 00:11:52,921
So, Zosima, remember, was in the army and was so brutal that he slapped his orderly so hard in the face that he was covered with blood.

110
00:11:53,400 --> 00:12:01,800
And then he, at that moment, having experienced that, he suddenly remembers Markle and throws himself on the ground, or I think he does.

111
00:12:01,800 --> 00:12:06,841
Anyway, certainly experiences that he never will do anything like that again.

112
00:12:07,721 --> 00:12:16,040
And even Markle has to have at least an understanding of what it would be to laugh at religion.

113
00:12:16,040 --> 00:12:17,961
But it doesn't last long.

114
00:12:18,280 --> 00:12:29,401
He gets tuberculosis and he's got galloping consumption, the doctor says, and he's going to die very soon.

115
00:12:29,400 --> 00:12:35,241
And as soon as he does, he gets a lot of, presumably has a high fever.

116
00:12:35,241 --> 00:12:37,721
The doctor says later he has a fever.

117
00:12:37,721 --> 00:12:41,281
And again, that's something that happens in his brain.

118
00:12:41,280 --> 00:12:41,960
Directly.

119
00:12:41,961 --> 00:12:43,641
We don't care whether he has a fever or not.

120
00:12:44,320 --> 00:12:54,961
I mean, because he has a high fever, he begins to have these sort of visions that he wouldn't have if he wasn't in a certain way going crazy.

121
00:12:54,961 --> 00:13:01,520
Remember, the doctors also say the mysterious visitor had gone crazy, only they think it's some problem with his heart.

122
00:13:02,081 --> 00:13:09,201
And again, Dostoevsky doesn't care that maybe there is a problem with his neurons because of his high fever.

123
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:23,201
The question is whether he sees whether that enables him to see something real about the universe that people normally don't see because their brain has sort of got too simple and solid a grip on ordinary reality.

124
00:13:23,200 --> 00:13:32,241
So he's going crazy with his high fever and sees things that other people don't see, but they're not just his imagination.

125
00:13:32,241 --> 00:13:35,921
And you know that because they have this amazing effect on people.

126
00:13:35,920 --> 00:13:44,001
Markle has an effect on Saseva and gets him to give up the duel and points, he's the finger that points him into the monastery.

127
00:13:44,001 --> 00:13:51,361
And Zosima has an amazing effect on Alyasha, which points him out of the monastery into the world.

128
00:13:51,361 --> 00:13:55,760
And all of this may well be the result of brain fever, but it doesn't matter.

129
00:13:56,081 --> 00:14:02,960
It's true in the sense that it counts, that it makes things happen, very important things happen.

130
00:14:02,960 --> 00:14:05,280
It saves Grushenka, for instance.

131
00:14:05,281 --> 00:14:07,601
So let's look at the middle of 327.

132
00:14:07,601 --> 00:14:09,601
A marvelous change passed over him.

133
00:14:09,601 --> 00:14:11,680
His spirit seemed transformed.

134
00:14:11,680 --> 00:14:13,200
He was transformed.

135
00:14:13,200 --> 00:14:34,681
He was transformed from a normal, selfish, philosophical, atheistic, secular guy into even more than a saint, into somebody who brings the agape-connected love into the world and exhibits it.

136
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:36,841
That's how he's transformed.

137
00:14:36,841 --> 00:14:38,521
So, and now what does he do?

138
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:46,200
When they try to do their religious things, the old nurse would come in and say, Let me light the lamp before the holy image, my dear.

139
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:51,480
Before this, he would have allowed it, would not have allowed it, and would have blown it out.

140
00:14:51,480 --> 00:14:53,480
Light it, light it, dear nurse.

141
00:14:53,480 --> 00:14:57,160
I was a wretch to have prevented you from doing it before, he says.

142
00:14:57,641 --> 00:15:01,641
Now he says sort of the existentializing thing.

143
00:15:01,641 --> 00:15:05,081
He says, You pray when you light the lamp, and I pray when I see you.

144
00:15:05,081 --> 00:15:07,240
So we're praying to the same God.

145
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:14,760
Meaning, it isn't the sort of magical thing of lighting the lamp or not lighting the lamp, but what lighting the lamp means.

146
00:15:14,760 --> 00:15:24,361
And it means to her some devotional thing, and it means to him that he's happy that she's doing the devotional thing.

147
00:15:25,240 --> 00:15:34,361
And that's now he's in this religious dimension, and he says to his mother at the bottom of the page, life is paradise, and we are all in paradise, but we refuse to see it.

148
00:15:34,361 --> 00:15:37,641
If we would, we would be in heaven on earth the next day.

149
00:15:37,641 --> 00:15:59,560
That's important because, and we'll come back to it, for him, Markle, and presumably Dostoevsky thinks for primitive Christianity before it got mixed up with philosophy and Greek thinking, it wasn't that heaven was someplace else in another world, higher and better and different than this one.

150
00:15:59,561 --> 00:16:07,320
Heaven is this world, if you understand it right and relate to it right in this kind of totally loving way.

151
00:16:07,321 --> 00:16:11,560
The same thing, remember, what Deer Kierkegaard says about the afterlife.

152
00:16:11,561 --> 00:16:14,561
He says that, well, maybe there's an afterlife and maybe there isn't.

153
00:16:13,561 --> 00:16:18,480
But what's important is whether you can experience bliss in this life.

154
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:29,920
Anything short of that, anything that says that this life you can't really be fulfilled, but there's another life in which you can, is already giving away much too much.

155
00:16:31,841 --> 00:16:34,400
That says, well, this world is a terrible world.

156
00:16:34,400 --> 00:16:35,521
We're just stuck in it.

157
00:16:35,521 --> 00:16:39,601
And you can't understand anymore why God created it and thought it was good.

158
00:16:39,601 --> 00:16:41,281
The Augustine has a problem with that.

159
00:16:41,281 --> 00:16:42,960
He thinks the world is terrible.

160
00:16:42,960 --> 00:16:48,720
It's always luring you away from this direct relation to God that I drew on the board.

161
00:16:48,720 --> 00:16:52,881
And the point is, this world is not terrible.

162
00:16:52,881 --> 00:16:57,121
It's not luring you away from a direct vision and experience of God.

163
00:16:57,121 --> 00:17:02,480
This world is the experience of God, of the connectedness.

164
00:17:02,480 --> 00:17:04,560
Okay, so he sees that.

165
00:17:04,561 --> 00:17:12,000
And he says, at the bottom of 327, dear ones, he would say, What have I done that you should love me?

166
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:13,440
How can you love anyone like me?

167
00:17:14,561 --> 00:17:19,040
How was I to not know I did not appreciate it before?

168
00:17:19,041 --> 00:17:21,200
Now comes an important sense.

169
00:17:21,200 --> 00:17:31,280
You're always supposed to be looking, remember, for where Dostoevsky is going to sort of hit you over the head and say, I've just existentialized the incarnation.

170
00:17:31,280 --> 00:17:38,240
I've restaged the original church and Jesus' original experience.

171
00:17:38,240 --> 00:17:39,361
And how does it happen?

172
00:17:39,361 --> 00:17:40,720
How does he tell you?

173
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:42,721
Well, it's the bottom of 327.

174
00:17:42,720 --> 00:17:47,121
Those of you who aren't steeped in Christian tradition won't recognize this.

175
00:17:47,121 --> 00:17:48,160
Some of you will.

176
00:17:48,160 --> 00:17:53,201
When the servants came in to him, he would say, Dear kind people, why are you doing so much for me?

177
00:17:53,200 --> 00:17:55,121
Do I deserve to be waited on?

178
00:17:55,121 --> 00:18:00,200
If it were God's will for me to live, I would wait on you, for all men should wait on one another.

179
00:17:58,480 --> 00:18:05,560
You recognize, I mean, that's what Jesus says when he washes or wipes the feet of Mary Magdalene.

180
00:18:06,200 --> 00:18:09,240
Not being Christian myself, I don't know it by heart.

181
00:18:09,240 --> 00:18:21,400
But I know that he's telling you, sort of, he's in a way, Mark is now plagiarizing Jesus or talking just like Jesus, talking literally what Jesus was saying.

182
00:18:21,400 --> 00:18:26,361
And that's important, just so Dostoevsky gets you to realize, gee, I've heard that somewhere before.

183
00:18:26,361 --> 00:18:27,160
Yeah, yeah, of course.

184
00:18:27,160 --> 00:18:30,200
That's a direct quote from the New Testament.

185
00:18:30,200 --> 00:18:39,080
So, and it goes on, Mother, darling, there must be servants and masters, but if so, I will be the servant of my servants.

186
00:18:39,081 --> 00:18:43,881
And another thing, everyone is sinned against all men, and everyone more than I.

187
00:18:43,881 --> 00:18:47,881
Well, that's, I don't think that's, I don't think that's something Jesus ever says.

188
00:18:47,881 --> 00:18:51,240
I mean, that's the thing that Dostoevsky teaches anything.

189
00:18:52,041 --> 00:19:06,121
Not only are we all connected in a positive way by agake love, but we're all connected in a negative way of hurting other people and doing things that make other people worse, even when we don't know it.

190
00:19:06,121 --> 00:19:09,320
That's the thing that Zosima makes such a fuss about.

191
00:19:09,321 --> 00:19:18,361
And then the doctor says at the bottom of 327, your son cannot last long, the doctor told my mother, the disease is affecting his brain.

192
00:19:18,361 --> 00:19:21,641
Well, I said, yeah, the disease is affecting his brain.

193
00:19:21,641 --> 00:19:22,521
So what?

194
00:19:22,521 --> 00:19:30,680
That doesn't mean that he isn't having a sort of a repeat of the original experience of Jesus.

195
00:19:30,680 --> 00:19:36,841
And that's what's important for Dostoevsky here, to get that experience.

196
00:19:36,841 --> 00:19:38,680
Now, let me see where I am.

197
00:19:39,561 --> 00:19:47,361
So he's transformed from cynical socialist into the dimension of love.

198
00:19:43,480 --> 00:19:48,480
I think I read that already.

199
00:19:51,841 --> 00:20:01,440
And he never goes back on his way of he never goes back to fasting and lighting the lamps and so forth.

200
00:20:01,440 --> 00:20:08,881
He doesn't go, and I'll explain why in a minute, but you have to notice, he never talks really Christian talk.

201
00:20:08,881 --> 00:20:16,080
He never says, yes, the icon is where you should be praying, nurse, and I'm going to pray to the icon too.

202
00:20:16,081 --> 00:20:22,881
He says, you pray to the icon, and I'll appreciate the fact that you're being devoted and praying to the icon.

203
00:20:24,561 --> 00:20:28,160
He's not demythologizing or demagicalizing.

204
00:20:28,160 --> 00:20:29,761
He's pre-magicalizing.

205
00:20:29,760 --> 00:20:47,040
That is, here's an understanding of this kind of love before it got put into the symbols and language and rituals of Christianity, which is the first thing that happens in the church or in the Christian community.

206
00:20:47,041 --> 00:20:51,121
And it's before it gets made into a church.

207
00:20:51,121 --> 00:20:54,240
And it's before it gets Platonized.

208
00:20:54,240 --> 00:21:00,881
He's just, and so he never says any sort of, as far as I know, if you find places that contradict it, let me know.

209
00:21:00,881 --> 00:21:08,081
He doesn't say anything specifically, magically gospel, New Testament-like.

210
00:21:08,321 --> 00:21:12,160
He says we're all servants of servants, but that's not magical.

211
00:21:12,160 --> 00:21:15,361
That's this experience of interconnectedness.

212
00:21:15,361 --> 00:21:16,641
He's got that.

213
00:21:16,641 --> 00:21:19,920
What he hasn't got is a way of talking about it.

214
00:21:19,920 --> 00:21:40,200
Now, that turns out to be important because if you want to ask yourself what happened to Markle, why did, why does, how do I put it, the two people who have the experience of the connectedness before Zosima has it, go crazy and die.

215
00:21:40,521 --> 00:21:44,200
That is the mysterious visitor and now Markle.

216
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:45,960
Why does that have to happen?

217
00:21:46,281 --> 00:21:52,841
And that is really tied up with why did Jesus have to die in an existentialized way?

218
00:21:53,160 --> 00:22:09,641
The idea is that this experience is so overpowering, so absolutely against everyday human nature of selfishness and protectedness and wanting other people to be your servants and not you theirs and everything.

219
00:22:09,641 --> 00:22:17,720
The whole way everyday life is organized and the whole way we can think about it and make sense of it is contradicted by this experience.

220
00:22:17,720 --> 00:22:22,201
I mean, take the extreme case that we should love the birds and the animals and ask forgiveness.

221
00:22:22,200 --> 00:22:23,400
That's crazy.

222
00:22:23,400 --> 00:22:32,601
Nothing in our experience suggests that we should do it or why we should do it or what good it would do to do it or what bad it would do not to do it.

223
00:22:32,841 --> 00:22:36,680
It's just an amazingly contradictory experience.

224
00:22:36,680 --> 00:22:41,720
And that's so that you can't live in this normal world once you see it.

225
00:22:41,720 --> 00:22:43,800
That's the moral.

226
00:22:43,801 --> 00:22:51,720
And so it looks like craziness once you see it because you can't really make, you can't explain to anybody what's going on.

227
00:22:52,361 --> 00:22:58,520
You can't relate to the people except in this way that they can't understand, which is this overwhelming love.

228
00:22:58,521 --> 00:23:14,561
So you end up, that is, at least in our existentialized way, Markle, the incarnation, the God-man is in our book, Jesus in our book, will definitely have to go crazy and die.

229
00:23:14,561 --> 00:23:16,320
He doesn't have to get crucified.

230
00:23:16,641 --> 00:23:18,321
Crucified is another issue.

231
00:23:13,480 --> 00:23:19,681
Dimitri gets crucified.

232
00:23:19,841 --> 00:23:27,440
Dimitri, Dostoevsky sort of divides up the various parts of being an incarnation.

233
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:31,680
I'm not going to get time to talk about Dimitri, so I'll just say it right now.

234
00:23:31,680 --> 00:23:36,080
Notice how Dimitri keeps talking about suffering and being crucified.

235
00:23:36,081 --> 00:23:51,680
And you will see that Dostoevsky is hitting you over the head to watch the way Dimitri suffers, because his suffering is the kind of suffering that is Christian suffering, which will lead to joy in the end.

236
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:54,561
And there's a whole story to be said about that.

237
00:23:54,561 --> 00:24:02,800
And anybody who wants to write about Dimitri and crucifixion can, that is, suffering, can do it.

238
00:24:02,801 --> 00:24:06,001
But Dostoevsky doesn't, he separates them on purpose.

239
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:19,040
There's the joy of getting in touch with this love, and then there's how to deal with getting in touch with your guilt for having caused very bad things in the world, more than you even realize.

240
00:24:19,041 --> 00:24:20,480
So now I'm going back to here.

241
00:24:20,480 --> 00:24:28,081
So he's got this pure love now, and he's got this extreme Christian vision.

242
00:24:28,081 --> 00:24:33,440
I'm just wanting to make sure I've read the passages I want, yeah, that we're in paradise and we don't see it.

243
00:24:33,440 --> 00:24:35,841
And that he's got brain fever.

244
00:24:35,841 --> 00:24:39,361
That's where we are, at the bottom of 3.28.

245
00:24:39,361 --> 00:24:45,601
And anybody who experiences this pure kind of love must go crazy.

246
00:24:45,920 --> 00:24:53,200
The idiot, too, another one of the Jesus figures in the book, Dostoevsky's book, The Idiot, goes crazy.

247
00:24:53,361 --> 00:24:54,400
It just happens.

248
00:24:54,960 --> 00:24:57,200
You just can't cope with it.

249
00:24:58,281 --> 00:25:10,841
So the question becomes: how come they can experience this love at all, given that they're selfish people like everybody else, and now they've experienced this total love?

250
00:25:10,841 --> 00:25:14,361
And the answer is, well, they can't really live that way.

251
00:25:14,361 --> 00:25:15,400
I'm just repeating myself.

252
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:22,040
They have no precedent for it, no language, no practices, no institutions, no way of making sense of it.

253
00:25:22,041 --> 00:25:29,080
They just experience this connectedness, and that makes them stop being normal, sane human beings.

254
00:25:29,081 --> 00:25:35,240
And Dostoevsky's way of describing that is they just look crazy.

255
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:38,920
And so now he's going off and looking crazy.

256
00:25:38,920 --> 00:25:41,321
That's where we have to see what's next.

257
00:25:43,561 --> 00:25:50,760
Then he talks about loving the birds and the animals at the bottom of 367.

258
00:25:50,760 --> 00:25:53,560
And you should pray to the birds.

259
00:25:54,841 --> 00:25:58,440
Consumed by an all-embracing love in a sort of transport.

260
00:25:58,440 --> 00:26:01,400
You see, he's just sort of, this is sort of his madness, just a typical.

261
00:26:01,561 --> 00:26:05,800
If somebody starts talking like that and thinking like that, they look crazy.

262
00:26:06,121 --> 00:26:10,520
You're consumed in an all-embracing love, in a sort of transport.

263
00:26:10,521 --> 00:26:13,560
You would pray that they too would forgive you, the animals.

264
00:26:13,561 --> 00:26:17,560
Treasure that ecstasy, however senseless it may seem to men.

265
00:26:17,561 --> 00:26:18,281
You see that?

266
00:26:18,281 --> 00:26:28,841
I mean, that's another way of saying, I'm experiencing something that if you experienced it, you should think it's a wonderful thing to experience it, even though it seems to you and everybody else crazy.

267
00:26:28,841 --> 00:26:31,321
And that's as far as we get with that.

268
00:26:31,321 --> 00:26:34,680
Michael dies and so forth.

269
00:26:35,240 --> 00:26:44,241
So, well, how then do these existentialized Jesus figures who are even crazier than Jesus?

270
00:26:44,400 --> 00:26:48,000
I don't think Jesus ever asked the birds for forgiveness.

271
00:26:48,000 --> 00:27:07,361
But these people who don't read the Bible, don't use the symbols from the Bible, don't sort of restrict agape love to other people the way the Bible does, how do they ever get into being sort of stable and sane Christians?

272
00:27:07,361 --> 00:27:10,480
And that's the next thing we have to talk about.

273
00:27:10,960 --> 00:27:11,840
Let me see now.

274
00:27:11,841 --> 00:27:14,320
I want to make sure we got everything.

275
00:27:14,641 --> 00:27:15,361
Yeah.

276
00:27:15,361 --> 00:27:27,920
Now, so I've now convinced you, I hope, or done my best, that if you have this experience, you seem crazy to yourself, and you seem crazy to everybody else, and in a certain sense, you are crazy.

277
00:27:27,920 --> 00:27:30,000
And then what happens?

278
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:49,841
Well, I already said what you need is a language, sort of rituals, shared experiences, institutions that make this intelligible and bring it under control so you're not in this sort of mind-blowing, literally mind-blowing state all the time.

279
00:27:49,841 --> 00:27:51,200
And what is that?

280
00:27:51,200 --> 00:27:52,641
Well, that's the church.

281
00:27:52,641 --> 00:28:03,920
The church takes this crazy experience and tames it and makes it intelligible by writing the Bible, for instance, the New Testament.

282
00:28:04,321 --> 00:28:06,241
They're all busy trying to explain it.

283
00:28:06,240 --> 00:28:11,200
Paul's trying his way, and John is trying his way, and none of them have got it very clear.

284
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:20,080
It turns out, if you look at the Bible carefully, some of them think there's a Trinity, some of them think there's a duality about God, some of them think there's only one.

285
00:28:21,361 --> 00:28:23,920
And it's all mixed up.

286
00:28:24,081 --> 00:28:29,081
But gradually, there are people who are called church fathers who work hard to straighten it all out.

287
00:28:29,641 --> 00:28:37,320
And they form, they write credos that state the things you have to believe if you're a Christian, and so forth.

288
00:28:37,321 --> 00:28:39,960
And that, now I want to give you the overall picture.

289
00:28:39,960 --> 00:28:47,720
That's the second stage of Dostoevsky's three-stage story about how the world is going to be saved.

290
00:28:47,720 --> 00:28:49,961
We've done the first stage, but I just didn't name it.

291
00:28:49,960 --> 00:28:58,041
The first stage is primitive Christianity before it has a language, before it has a church, before it knows what it's doing.

292
00:28:58,361 --> 00:28:59,400
And we just did that.

293
00:28:59,400 --> 00:29:04,520
Markle is primitive Christianity at stage one.

294
00:29:04,841 --> 00:29:08,841
Who would be the next stage in our book?

295
00:29:08,841 --> 00:29:10,200
Zosima, yes.

296
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:12,761
The next stage is to institutionalize it.

297
00:29:12,760 --> 00:29:19,480
They withdraw from the world because the world is too worldly and secular for them.

298
00:29:19,480 --> 00:29:21,960
It can't support this kind of love and craziness.

299
00:29:21,960 --> 00:29:32,440
You can't go around on the street falling on your knees at the beggars and saying you're worse than they are and you're very sorry that you're so evil.

300
00:29:32,760 --> 00:29:34,200
Anyway, it's all crazy.

301
00:29:34,361 --> 00:29:36,761
You can't go around talking to all the animals all the time.

302
00:29:36,760 --> 00:29:38,200
They'll certainly lock you up.

303
00:29:38,200 --> 00:29:45,641
But anyway, by the time you fix it, you make it into a shared way of life.

304
00:29:45,960 --> 00:29:50,200
And you withdraw from these people in the world who can't understand you and think you're crazy.

305
00:29:50,200 --> 00:29:57,881
And you find a language in which you're not crazy anymore because you can understand each other and confess and love each other and so forth.

306
00:29:57,881 --> 00:29:59,560
And that is stage two.

307
00:30:00,440 --> 00:30:05,240
So we have to look at stage two, because that's where most of the book takes place.

308
00:30:07,240 --> 00:30:22,641
So when Markle's love gets stored up in Zosima, when it finally breaks out in Zosima, when he feels terrible about what he did to his orderly and throws away his gun at the duel and says, look, the world is beautiful and everybody should love everybody.

309
00:30:23,041 --> 00:30:31,920
When that happens, then Marko has pointed the way to the monastery, Zosima says.

310
00:30:31,920 --> 00:30:55,121
That's Zosima's kind of, I don't know, poetic or magical or Christian way of saying that thanks to having been loved by his brother and seeing his brother exhibit this kind of love, he is drawn to go into this institution where the love is preserved.

311
00:30:55,760 --> 00:30:58,400
And I think maybe that's on 329.

312
00:30:58,401 --> 00:30:59,680
I mean, I don't want to snow.

313
00:30:59,760 --> 00:31:01,360
No, that's when he passes it on.

314
00:31:01,360 --> 00:31:03,121
So let me go further.

315
00:31:03,121 --> 00:31:08,721
So that's the apostolic succession, and Marko is in it.

316
00:31:08,720 --> 00:31:13,680
And Zosima receive a kind of ordination from Markle.

317
00:31:13,680 --> 00:31:18,720
That's when Marko puts his hands on him, and Alyasha receives it from Zosima.

318
00:31:18,720 --> 00:31:22,880
I'll just mention that, but I'm going to go back to talking about Zosima.

